<FONT CLASS="title16">How to Plate</FONT><BR> 
<font class="bodyCopySmall">
A plate of cheese is an elegant supper, a country lunch, a prelude to 
dessert. The rule is, the simpler the better.
<P>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" BORDER="0" WIDTH="379">
	<TR VALIGN="top">
		<TD WIDTH="15" class="bodyCopySmall"><img src="/media_stat/images/template/cheese/green_bullett.gif" 
			width="6" height="6" border="0" HSPACE="4" VSPACE="3" ALIGN="RIGHT"></TD>
		<TD WIDTH="364"  class="bodyCopySmall">A single plate for the table, passed around, is more convenient and economical than a 
			separate plate for everyone. Two ounces of cheese per person is plenty.<BR><BR></TD> 
	</TR>
	<TR VALIGN="top">
		<TD WIDTH="15"><img src="/media_stat/images/template/cheese/green_bullett.gif" 
			width="6" height="6" border="0" HSPACE="4" VSPACE="3" ALIGN="RIGHT"></TD>
		<TD WIDTH="364" class="bodyCopySmall">Don't overwhelm your guests. Serve one perfect cheese, two in perfect 
			contrast, three or four to explore different flavors and textures. Five is pushing it.<BR><BR></TD>
	<TR VALIGN="top">
		<TD WIDTH="15"><img src="/media_stat/images/template/cheese/green_bullett.gif" 
			width="6" height="6" border="0" HSPACE="4" VSPACE="3" ALIGN="RIGHT"></TD>
		<TD WIDTH="364" class="bodyCopySmall">Garnish your cheese plate with nuts, dried fruit, or a little chutney or preserves. Be creative, 
			but don't crowd the plate. Serve bread and crackers or fresh fruit on the side.<BR><BR></TD>
	</TR>
	<TR VALIGN="top">
		<TD WIDTH="15"><img src="/media_stat/images/template/cheese/green_bullett.gif" 
			width="6" height="6" border="0" HSPACE="4" VSPACE="3" ALIGN="RIGHT"></TD>
		<TD WIDTH="364" class="bodyCopySmall">Choose cheeses of contrasting flavors, intensities, types of milk, and textures.<BR><BR></TD>
	</TR>
	<TR VALIGN="top">
		<TD WIDTH="15"><img src="/media_stat/images/template/cheese/green_bullett.gif" 
			width="6" height="6" border="0" HSPACE="4" VSPACE="3" ALIGN="RIGHT"></TD>
		<TD WIDTH="364" class="bodyCopySmall">Let the cheeses come to room temperature before serving, as you would a 
			great red wine. Only then can the cheese reach its perfect texture and complexity.<BR></TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE>

